# Bandit Level 11 → Level 12

## Objective
The goal of this level was to find the password for the next level.  
The password was stored in the file `data.txt`, where all lowercase (`a-z`) and uppercase (`A-Z`) letters had been rotated by 13 positions.

---

## Challenge
This level introduced text transformation commands, which I was quite new to.  
The challenge also provided a list of commands that might help solve the level, including:

grep, sort, uniq, strings, base64, tr, tar, gzip, bzip2, and xxd

I was glad to come across this because it introduced me to commands I had not used before.

To understand the `tr` command better, I used a helpful website that explains Linux commands and examples:

https://tldr.inbrowser.app/pages/common/tr

While reading through the examples, I found this command:

tr < path/to/file "[:lower:]" "[:upper:]"

which translates lowercase letters into uppercase letters.

I experimented with this idea using the challenge file.

---

## Steps I Took

I used the following command:

tr < data.txt "[:lower:]" "[:upper:]"

This converted all lowercase letters in the file to uppercase letters.

The output became:

GUR CNFFJBEQ VF 7K16JARUVV5LXVUJFSSVDBBTAHGLW9D4

At this point, I realised the text was still encoded and that the challenge was referring to ROT13, where letters are rotated by 13 positions in the alphabet.

I then used the correct ROT13 translation command:

tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m' < data.txt

This decoded the text and revealed the password for the next level.

---

## Password for Level 12
7x16WNeHIi5YkIhWsfFIqoognUTyj9Q4

---

## Commands Learned

### tr
The `tr` command translates or replaces characters from standard input.

### tr "[:lower:]" "[:upper:]"
Converts lowercase letters into uppercase letters.

### ROT13
ROT13 rotates letters by 13 positions in the alphabet.

### tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m'
This command performs ROT13 translation on text.

### <
The `<` symbol redirects a file into a command as input.
